Comment: The Caro-Kann and variations fascinate me, so I've decided to start learning it.  However, I find some of the moves counter-intuitive so I never yet have played it straight.

Take the middle; fair enough.
If 3. e5, then Nd5 anchors the middle for Black for a bit.  3. ... Ne4 seems too risky, even if 4. f3 weakens the King-side for White a bit.
Not 3. ...d5, where 4. e5 drives the knight back to d7 (4. ... Ng4 is chased by 5. h3).

Not bad in itself as it develops the bishop, but I wonder whether 5. c4 threatening 6. Ng5 might have been better for maintaining tempo for White.
White is fully developed on the most standard lines, barring castling.  Black is relatively undeveloped, especially hampered by the Queen's knight, but quite safe for the mean time.

A curious move.  It looks like an attempt to force the issue on e5, while supporting the c4 bishop as well.  Not necessarily a bad idea, but perhaps castling first was in order, forcing Black to move out, where he has few options.
Threatens the newly-uncovered QP, but probably unwise, as it stunts Black's Queen-side further.
